        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A healthy BMI for a teenager is between the 5th and 85th percentile for their age and sex, based on CDC 2000 growth charts. For example, a healthy BMI for a 15-year-old boy is approximately 16.8 to 23.6, and for a 15-year-old girl approximately 16.4 to 24.4. Because normal BMI ranges change every year during adolescence, percentile-based interpretation is more accurate than fixed adult thresholds." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a normal BMI for a 15-year-old?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For a 15-year-old boy, healthy weight (5th to 85th percentile) corresponds to a BMI of approximately 16.8 to 23.6. For a 15-year-old girl it is approximately 16.4 to 24.4. The 50th percentile (median BMI) is approximately 20.2 for boys and 20.2 for girls at age 15." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "At what BMI is a teenager overweight?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A teenager is overweight when their BMI-for-age reaches the 85th percentile for their age and sex. This threshold changes at every age. For a 15-year-old boy it is approximately BMI 23.6; for a 15-year-old girl approximately BMI 24.4. At or above the 95th percentile is obese." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does puberty affect BMI in teenagers?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, significantly. During female puberty, oestrogen drives an increase in body fat, particularly in the hips, thighs, and breasts - this is biologically normal and healthy. During male puberty, testosterone drives rapid muscle mass and bone density gains, which increases weight without adding fat. The same BMI in a 16-year-old boy and girl therefore represents very different body compositions. A BMI that appears elevated in a teenage boy may largely reflect muscle gain rather than excess fat." }
      },
